# Collection expressions

Use **C# 12 collection expressions** (`[]`, `[a, b, c]`, `[..src, extra]`) when constructing arrays, spans, lists, or any collection target type the compiler can infer.

## Preferred

```csharp
string[] roles = ["admin", "operator", "viewer"];
ImmutableArray<int> ids = [1, 2, 3];
List<Tag> tags = [];
ReadOnlySpan<byte> header = [0x01, 0x02, 0x03];

string[] all = [..defaults, ..overrides];
```

## Avoid

```csharp
// Avoid
string[] roles = new string[] { "admin", "operator", "viewer" };
List<Tag> tags = new List<Tag>();
string[] empty = Array.Empty<string>();
string[] all = defaults.Concat(overrides).ToArray();
```

## Scope

- Use `[]` for empty literals; the compiler picks the best target representation.
- Use spread `..` for concatenation and prepend/append patterns.
- Concrete-type rule still applies on the **left**: `List<Tag> tags = [];`, **not** `var tags = new List<Tag>();`.
- Stay with explicit constructors only when you need a specific capacity, comparer, or other ctor argument.
